Motorists can expect another price hike for all grades of petrol next month.The Department of Energy yesterday, cited the depreciation of the rand against the US dollar as a reason for the hike.Petrol users will now pay an extra 49c a litre while diesel users can expect an increase between 30c and 32c a litre.Paraffin users will be paying between 34c and 46c a litre and liquefied petroleum gas users will pay 96c more. The Department of Energy said that the average international product prices of petrol, diesel and illuminating paraffin increased during the period being reviewed. In the period between March 31 and April 25, the average rand-US dollar exchange rate was R13.51 compared to R12.91 during the period prior. These changes led to a higher contribution to the basic fuels price on petrol, diesel and illuminating paraffin by 26.83c/l, 25.48c/l and 25.33c/l respectively, the department said.business@thenewage.co.za